  "response_text": "This is a comprehensive gluten-free meal plan designed to be balanced, flavorful, and easy to follow. It avoids all sources of wheat, barley, rye, and cross-contaminated oats.\n\n**Important Note:** Always check labels for gluten-containing additives (e.g., modified food starch, malt flavoring, soy sauce). Use certified gluten-free oats.\n\n### General Guidelines for the Week\n\n- **Breakfast:** Focus on protein + healthy fat to stabilize blood sugar.\n- **Lunch:** Leftovers from dinner or a simple salad/protein bowl.\n- **Dinner:** A balanced plate of protein, vegetables, and a gluten-free starch.\n- **Snacks:** Keep it simple—fruit, nuts, yogurt, or veggie sticks.\n\n---\n\n### Day 1: Monday\n\n- **Breakfast:** Scrambled eggs with spinach, feta cheese, and sliced avocado. Side of fresh berries.\n- **Lunch:** Large salad with grilled chicken, mixed greens, cucumber, cherry tomatoes, olives, and a lemon-olive oil vinaigrette.\n- **Dinner:** **Sheet Pan Lemon Herb Salmon** with roasted asparagus and sweet potato wedges (tossed in olive oil, salt, pepper, and rosemary).\n- **Snack:** A handful of almonds and a small apple.\n\n### Day 2: Tuesday\n\n- **Breakfast:** Gluten-free oatmeal (certified) made with almond milk, topped with sliced banana, walnuts, and a drizzle of maple syrup.\n- **Lunch:** Leftover salmon and sweet potato from Monday.\n- **Dinner:** **Beef & Vegetable Stir-fry** (use tamari or coconut aminos instead of soy sauce). Serve over steamed white or brown rice.\n- **Snack:** Celery sticks with almond butter.\n\n### Day 3: Wednesday\n\n- **Breakfast:** Greek yogurt (plain) with gluten-free granola and fresh strawberries.\n- **Lunch:** **Quinoa Power Bowl:** Quinoa, black beans, corn, diced bell peppers, avocado, and a lime-cilantro dressing.\n- **Dinner:** **Chicken Tikka Masala** (made with canned coconut milk and tomato paste, using garam masala and turmeric). Serve with cauliflower rice or basmati rice.\n- **Snack:** A pear or a handful of grapes.\n\n### Day 4: Thursday\n\n- **Breakfast:** Two hard-boiled eggs, a slice of gluten-free toast (e.g., Udi's or Canyon Bakehouse) with avocado, and a side of mixed berries.\n- **Lunch:** Leftover Chicken Tikka Masala and rice.\n- **Dinner:** **Stuffed Bell Peppers:** Ground turkey or beef mixed with cooked quinoa, diced tomatoes, onions, and spices. Baked until tender. Top with shredded cheese.\n- **Snack:** Baby carrots with hummus.\n\n### Day 5: Friday\n\n- **Breakfast:** Smoothie: 1 cup unsweetened almond milk, 1 scoop gluten-free protein powder (or plain Greek yogurt), 1/2 banana, 1 cup spinach, 1 tbsp chia seeds.\n- **Lunch:** **Tuna Salad Lettuce Wraps:** Mix canned tuna with mashed avocado, lemon juice, salt, and pepper. Spoon into large romaine lettuce leaves. Add sliced cucumber.\n- **Dinner:** **Zucchini Noodles (Zoodles) with Pesto & Shrimp:** Sauté zucchini noodles in olive oil, add cooked shrimp, and toss with gluten-free pesto (check label). Add cherry tomatoes.\n- **Snack:** A small handful of dark chocolate chips and walnuts.\n\n### Day 6: Saturday\n\n- **Breakfast:** **Sweet Potato Hash:** Diced sweet potato, onion, and bell pepper sautéed in coconut oil. Top with two fried eggs.\n- **Lunch:** Leftover Zoodles or a simple mixed greens salad with grilled chicken.\n- **Dinner:** **Taco Night:** Use corn tortillas (or large lettuce leaves). Fill with seasoned ground beef, black beans, shredded lettuce, diced tomatoes, cheese, salsa, and guacamole.\n- **Snack:** A sliced mango or apple with sunflower seed butter.\n\n### Day 7: Sunday\n\n- **Breakfast:** **Gluten-Free Pancakes** (made with almond flour or a gluten-free all-purpose blend). Top with fresh blueberries and a dollop of yogurt.\n- **Lunch:** **Loaded Baked Potato:** Top a baked potato with broccoli, cheddar cheese, a dollop of sour cream, and leftover taco meat.\n- **Dinner:** **Roasted Chicken Thighs** (seasoned with paprika, garlic powder, and thyme) with roasted Brussels sprouts and a side of wild rice.\n- **Snack:** A small bowl of mixed berries.\n\n---\n\n### Sample Snack List (Mix & Match)\n\n- **Produce:** Apple slices, bananas, berries, carrot sticks, bell pepper strips, cucumber rounds.\n- **Protein:** Hard-boiled eggs, string cheese, beef jerky (check label), edamame.\n- **Fat/Protein:** Almonds, walnuts, sunflower seeds, pumpkin seeds, cashews.\n- **Dips:** Hummus, guacamole, almond butter, tahini.\n- **Dairy:** Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, cheese cubes.\n- **Grains:** Gluten-free crackers (e.g., Mary's Gone Crackers, Simple Mills), rice cakes.\n\n### Key Tips for Success\n\n1.  **Read Every Label:** Gluten hides in soy sauce, salad dressings, marinades, broths, soups, and even some spice blends.\n2.  **Go for Whole Foods:** The safest and most nutritious gluten-free meals are based on whole, unprocessed foods: vegetables, fruits, lean meats, fish, eggs, beans, nuts, seeds, and naturally gluten-free grains (rice, quinoa, corn, buckwheat).\n3.  **Watch for Cross-Contamination:** Use separate cutting boards, toasters, and colanders for gluten-free foods if you share a kitchen.\n4.  **Don't Forget Fiber:** Many gluten-free substitutes lack fiber. Prioritize vegetables, fruits, beans, lentils, and seeds (chia, flax) to stay regular.\n5.  **Stay Hydrated:** Drink plenty of water throughout the day.\n\nThis plan is a template. Feel free to swap days, substitute proteins, and use whatever vegetables are in season. Enjoy your delicious, gluten-free week",
